r\n!Song Title\n!Romanized Title\n!Label\n|-\n|\n2020\n|\u0e04\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e01\u0e39\n|[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=leevExpA8ec Kan Goo]\n|[[GMM Grammy]]\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Twitter|bbrightvc}}\n* {{Instagram|bbrightvc}} (personal)\n* {{Instagram|isawitbefore}} (photography)\n* {{IMDb name | nm11456308 | Vachirawit Chiva-aree }}\n\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Thai people of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Thai people of American descent]]\n[[Category:Thai male models]]\n[[Category:21st-century Thai male actors]]\n[[Category:Thai male actors]]\n[[Category:Thai male television actors]]\n[[Category:People from Nakhon Pathom Province]]\n", "name_user": "PradaSaetiew", "label": "safe", "comment": "add his birth name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vachirawit_Chiva-aree"}
{"title_page": "Suzie Sheehy", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian physicist and science communicator}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Suzie Sheehy\n| birth_name = Suzanne Lyn Sheehy\n| image = Dr. Suzie Sheehy.jpg\n| fields = [[Accelerator physics]]\n| caption = Suzie Sheehy\n| thesis_title = Design of a non-scaling fixed field alternating gradient accelerator for charged particle therapy\n| awards = [[Royal Society University Research Fellowship]] (2017)\n| thesis_year = 2010\n| thesis_url = http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.533881\n| doctoral_advisor = Kenneth Peach<ref name=ssdphil/>\n| workplaces = [[University of Oxford]]<br>[[Rutherford Appleton Laboratory]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Melbourne]] (BS)<br>[[University of Oxford]] (DPhil)\n| website = {{URL|suziesheehy.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Suzanne Lyn Sheehy''' is an Australian accelerator physicist and science communicator at the [[University of Oxford]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSheehy was born in [[Mildura]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.profmagazine.com/single-post/2017/04/18/proFile-of-Suzie-Sheehy|title=proFile of Suzie Sheehy|website=profmagazine.com|language=en|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> She moved to Melbourne as a child, and was inspired to study physics at a young age by her teachers at Parkdale Primary and Mentone Girls\u2019 Grammar School.<ref name=\":0\" /> She completed her undergraduate studies at the [[University of Melbourne]] in 2006.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www2.physics.ox.ac.uk/contacts/people/sheehy|title=Suzie Sheehy {{!}} University of Oxford Department of Physics|website=www2.physics.ox.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> In 2010 she earned a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] from the [[University of Oxford]], where she worked in the John Adams Institute for Accelerator Science.<ref name=\":1\" />  Her DPhil was part of the PAMELA project, focussed on designing non-scaling [[FFAG accelerator]]s for charged particle therapy<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.astec.stfc.ac.uk/Pages/Suzie-Sheehy-Research-Fellow.aspx|title=ASTEC: Suzie Sheehy - Research Fellow|website=www.astec.stfc.ac.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> supervised by Kenneth Peach.<ref name=ssdphil>{{cite thesis|degree=DPhil|publisher=University of Oxford|url=http://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:d9cd977c-35db-45cc-ad33-67710fc3e82f|title=Design of a non-scaling fixed field alternating gradient accelerator for charged particle therapy|first= Suzanne Lyn|last=Sheehy|date=2010|id={{EThOS|uk.bl.ethos.533881}}|website=ora.ox.ac.uk|oclc=757139208}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career ==\nIn 2010 Sheehy was awarded a [[Royal Commission for the Exhibition of 1851]] fellowship in high intensity hadron accelerators.<ref name=\":1\" /> She was part of the collaboration that achieved the first compact electron accelerator [[EMMA (accelerator)|EMMA]] in 2011.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://impact.ref.ac.uk/CaseStudies/CaseStudy.aspx?Id=18322|title=REF Case study search|website=impact.ref.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> She was appointed to a joint position in Intense Hadron Accelerators with the [[University of Oxford]] and [[Science and Technology Facilities Council]] (STFC) in 2015, and is now a [[Royal Society University Research Fellowship|Royal Society University Research Fellow]] at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Public engagement ===\nSheehy is an award-winning science communicator and public speaker. Working with Emmanuel Tsesmelis, during her DPhil Sheehy designed a particle physics outreach show ''Accelerate!'' for 11- to 18-year-old children in the [[United Kingdom]] which later also ran in [[Germany]].<ref name=\":2\" /> She was responsible for training presenters and delivering shows and workshops.<ref name=\":2\" /> The training was delivered as part the [[CERN]] teacher educational program.<ref name=\":2\" /> As part of the program, they made a YouTube video explaining ''How to Make a Cloud Chamber''. It has received over 100,000 views.<ref>{{Citation|last=Steele|first=Andrew|title=How to make a cloud chamber|date=12 July 2011|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=400xfGmSlqQ|website=youtube.com|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> Sheehy worked with the [[Royal Institution]] to create videos about particle accelerators.<ref>{{Citation|last=The Royal Institution|title=Suzie Sheehy - Thorium Fuelled Particle Accelerators|date=18 December 2012|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OJTP93ptTI|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLbnrZHfNEDZx0mVe9wGxg5kyKdofRJJ7m|title=Particle Accelerators for Humanity - YouTube|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> She gave the 2012 National Space Academy keynote talk.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalspaceacademy.org/previous-keynote-speakers/271-dr-suzie-sheehy|title=National Space Academy - Dr Suzie Sheehy|last=User|first=Super|website=nationalspaceacademy.org|language=en-gb|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> She appeared on [[Discovery Channel]]'s [[Impossible Engineering]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm9005521/|title=Suzie Sheehy|website=IMDb|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> She was a speaker at 2018 [[TED (conference)|TED]]<nowiki/>x Sydney.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tedxsydney.com/contributor/suzie-sheehy/|title=Suzie Sheehy - TEDxSydney|work=TEDxSydney|access-date=21 June 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards and honours ===\n* 2017 awarded a [[Royal Society University Research Fellowship]] (URF).<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/suzie-sheehy-13477/|title=Suzie Sheehy|website=royalsociety.org|publisher=[[Royal Society]]|location=London|author=Anon|year=2017|language=en-gb|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n* 2016 [[Institute of Physics]] HEPP Group Science in Society Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iop.org/activity/groups/subject/hepp/prize/society/page_40790.html|title=HEPP Group Science in Society Prize Winners|last=Physics|first=Institute of|website=www.iop.org|language=en-GB|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n* 2010 [[University of Oxford]] Vice Chancellors Civic Award<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oxfordstudent.com/2010/06/10/vc-honours-student-civic-campaigners/|title=VC honours student civic campaigners \u2013 The Oxford Student|date=10 June 2010|work=The Oxford Student|access-date=21 June 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n* 2010 [[British Science Association]] Lord Kelvin Award<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheehy, Suzie}}\n[[Category:Particle physicists]]\n[[Category:Australian women physicists]]\n[[Category:Australian physicists]]\n[[Category:University of Melbourne alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Science communicators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Australian physicist and science communicator}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Suzie Sheehy\n| birth_name = Suzanne Lyn Sheehy\n| image = Dr. Suzie Sheehy.jpg\n| fields = [[Accelerator physics]]\n| caption = Suzie Sheehy\n| thesis_title = Design of a non-scaling fixed field alternating gradient accelerator for charged particle therapy\n| awards = [[Royal Society University Research Fellowship]] (2017)\n| thesis_year = 2010\n| thesis_url = http://ethos.bl.uk/OrderDetails.do?uin=uk.bl.ethos.533881\n| doctoral_advisor = Kenneth Peach<ref name=ssdphil/>\n| workplaces = [[University of Oxford]]<br>[[Rutherford Appleton Laboratory]]\n| alma_mater = [[University of Melbourne]] (BS)<br>[[University of Oxford]] (DPhil)\n| website = {{URL|suziesheehy.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Suzanne Lyn Sheehy''' is an Australian accelerator physicist and science communicator at the [[University of Oxford]].\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSheehy was born in [[Mildura]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.profmagazine.com/single-post/2017/04/18/proFile-of-Suzie-Sheehy|title=proFile of Suzie Sheehy|website=profmagazine.com|language=en|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> She moved to Melbourne as a child, and was inspired to study physics at a young age by her teachers at Parkdale Primary and Mentone Girls\u2019 Grammar School.<ref name=\":0\" /> She completed her undergraduate studies at the [[University of Melbourne]] in 2006.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www2.physics.ox.ac.uk/contacts/people/sheehy|title=Suzie Sheehy {{!}} University of Oxford Department of Physics|website=www2.physics.ox.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> In 2010 she earned a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] from the [[University of Oxford]], where she worked in the John Adams Institute for Accelerator Science.<ref name=\":1\" />  Her DPhil was part of the PAMELA project, focussed on designing non-scaling [[FFAG accelerator]]s for charged particle therapy<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.astec.stfc.ac.uk/Pages/Suzie-Sheehy-Research-Fellow.aspx|title=ASTEC: Suzie Sheehy - Research Fellow|website=www.astec.stfc.ac.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> supervised by Kenneth Peach.<ref name=ssdphil>{{cite thesis|degree=DPhil|publisher=University of Oxford|url=http://ora.ox.ac.uk/objects/uuid:d9cd977c-35db-45cc-ad33-67710fc3e82f|title=Design of a non-scaling fixed field alternating gradient accelerator for charged particle therapy|first= Suzanne Lyn|last=Sheehy|date=2010|id={{EThOS|uk.bl.ethos.533881}}|website=ora.ox.ac.uk|oclc=757139208}} {{free access}}</ref>\n\n== Research and career ==\nIn 2010 Sheehy was awarded a [[Royal Commission for the Exhibition of 1851]] fellowship in high intensity hadron accelerators.<ref name=\":1\" /> She was part of the collaboration that achieved the first compact electron accelerator [[EMMA (accelerator)|EMMA]] in 2011.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://impact.ref.ac.uk/CaseStudies/CaseStudy.aspx?Id=18322|title=REF Case study search|website=impact.ref.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> She was appointed to a joint position in Intense Hadron Accelerators with the [[University of Oxford]] and [[Science and Technology Facilities Council]] (STFC) in 2015, and is now a [[Royal Society University Research Fellowship|Royal Society University Research Fellow]] at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Public engagement ===\nSheehy is an award-winning science communicator and public speaker. Working with Emmanuel Tsesmelis, during her DPhil Sheehy designed a particle physics outreach show ''Accelerate!'' for 11- to 18-year-old children in the [[United Kingdom]] which later also ran in [[Germany]].<ref name=\":2\" /> She was responsible for training presenters and delivering shows and workshops.<ref name=\":2\" /> The training was delivered as part the [[CERN]] teacher educational program.<ref name=\":2\" /> As part of the program, they made a YouTube video explaining ''How to Make a Cloud Chamber''. It has received over 100,000 views.<ref>{{Citation|last=Steele|first=Andrew|title=How to make a cloud chamber|date=12 July 2011|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=400xfGmSlqQ|website=youtube.com|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> Sheehy worked with the [[Royal Institution]] to create videos about particle accelerators.<ref>{{Citation|last=The Royal Institution|title=Suzie Sheehy - Thorium Fuelled Particle Accelerators|date=18 December 2012|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9OJTP93ptTI|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLbnrZHfNEDZx0mVe9wGxg5kyKdofRJJ7m|title=Particle Accelerators for Humanity - YouTube|website=YouTube|language=en|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> She gave the 2012 National Space Academy keynote talk.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalspaceacademy.org/previous-keynote-speakers/271-dr-suzie-sheehy|title=National Space Academy - Dr Suzie Sheehy|last=User|first=Super|website=nationalspaceacademy.org|language=en-gb|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> She appeared on [[Discovery Channel]]'s Impossible Engineering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm9005521/|title=Suzie Sheehy|website=IMDb|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref> She was a speaker at 2018 [[TED (conference)|TED]]<nowiki/>x Sydney.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://tedxsydney.com/contributor/suzie-sheehy/|title=Suzie Sheehy - TEDxSydney|work=TEDxSydney|access-date=21 June 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Awards and honours ===\n* 2017 awarded a [[Royal Society University Research Fellowship]] (URF).<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/suzie-sheehy-13477/|title=Suzie Sheehy|website=royalsociety.org|publisher=[[Royal Society]]|location=London|author=Anon|year=2017|language=en-gb|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n* 2016 [[Institute of Physics]] HEPP Group Science in Society Award<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iop.org/activity/groups/subject/hepp/prize/society/page_40790.html|title=HEPP Group Science in Society Prize Winners|last=Physics|first=Institute of|website=www.iop.org|language=en-GB|access-date=21 June 2018}}</ref>\n* 2010 [[University of Oxford]] Vice Chancellors Civic Award<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.oxfordstudent.com/2010/06/10/vc-honours-student-civic-campaigners/|title=VC honours student civic campaigners \u2013 The Oxford Student|date=10 June 2010|work=The Oxford Student|access-date=21 June 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n* 2010 [[British Science Association]] Lord Kelvin Award<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sheehy, Suzie}}\n[[Category:Particle physicists]]\n[[Category:Australian women physicists]]\n[[Category:Australian physicists]]\n[[Category:University of Melbourne alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Science communicators]]\n", "name_user": "Kj cheetham", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePublic engagement:Added wikilink", "url_page": "//