{"title_page": "Love Hurts (Cher album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Love Hurts\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Cher]]\n| cover      = Cher-Love Hurts-Frontal.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = June 13, 1991 <small>(OCE)</small><br />June 17, 1991 <small>(UK)</small><br />June 18, 1991 <small>(US)</small>\n| recorded   = 1989{{ndash}}91\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Pop rock]]|[[adult contemporary music|adult contemporary]]}}\n| length     = 43:55 <small>(North American edition)</small><br />46:45 <small>(Oceanian/European edition)</small>\n| label      = [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n| producer   = {{hlist|[[John Kalodner]]|[[Peter Asher]]|[[Steve Lukather]]|[[Guy Roche]]|[[Diane Warren]]|[[Richie Zito]]|[[Bob Rock]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Mermaids (soundtrack)|Mermaids]]\n| prev_year  = 1990\n| next_title = [[Greatest Hits: 1965\u20131992]]\n| next_year  = 1992\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = studio\n | cover   = Cher - Love Hurts.png\n | border  = yes\n | alt     =\n | caption = Oceanian and European cover art, also used for digital release\n}}\n{{Singles\n | name        = Love Hurts\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Love and Understanding]]\n | single1date = May 21, 1991\n | single2     = [[Save Up All Your Tears]]\n | single2date = October 7, 1991\n | single3     = [[Love Hurts]]\n | single3date = December 1991\n | single4     = [[Could've Been You]]\n | single4date = February 1992\n | single5     = [[When Lovers Become Strangers]]\n | single5date = March 1992\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Love Hurts''''' is the twentieth studio album by American singer-actress [[Cher]], released on June 13, 1991 by [[Geffen Records]]. The [[RIAA]] certified it Gold on August 27, 1991. It is the final studio album with the record label Geffen. The lead single from the album was, \"[[Love and Understanding]]\" and the follow-up singles were \"[[Save Up All Your Tears]]\", \"[[Love Hurts]]\", \"[[Could've Been You]]\" and \"[[When Lovers Become Strangers]]\". It peaked at number 48 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' Top 200]] albums chart with the sales of 19,000. In November 2011, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' stated that ''Love Hurts'' has sold 600,000 copies in the US.<ref name=\"ussales\">[http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/465290/ask-billboard-twice-is-nice-twice-for-adele?page=0%2C1 Ask Billboard: Twice Is Nice, Twice, for Adele]</ref>\n\n==Album information==\n''Love Hurts'' was released in 1991 and was the third and final studio album released by [[Cher]] for [[Geffen Records]]. The record featured production by [[Bob Rock]] and saw her continue to collaborate with [[John Kalodner]], [[Diane Warren]] and [[Desmond Child]]. The album was recorded in late 1990/early 1991, during the first year of Cher's relationship to [[Bon Jovi|Bon Jovi's]] guitarist [[Richie Sambora]]. She dedicated the album to him and \"every man that ever made me shed a tear\".\n\nThe album contained four covers: \"[[Save Up All Your Tears]]\" recorded in the late 1980s by [[Bonnie Tyler]] and [[Robin Beck]], the [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]] song \"[[A World Without Heroes]]\" recorded in 1981, \"Fires Of Eden\" recorded by [[Judy Collins]] in 1990, and \"[[Love Hurts]]\" a remake of the 1975 version which Cher had previously recorded for her album ''[[Stars (Cher album)|Stars]]''. This time the song was more [[pop/rock]] rather than a ballad. The original version was released by [[Everly Brothers]] in 1960; however, the most popular version of the song (and the only rendition of \"Love Hurts\" to become a hit single in the United States, reaching No. 8 on the Billboard Hot 100 in early 1976) was the one recorded by Scottish [[hard rock]] band [[Nazareth (band)|Nazareth]]. In addition, the European version of the album also contains the worldwide hit \"[[The Shoop Shoop Song (It's in His Kiss)]]\" (originally recorded by Betty Everett <ref>w</ref> in 1963), which was released as a single in the United States in 1990 (prior to the release of the \"Love Hurts\" album to promote Cher's film ''[[Mermaids (1990 film)|Mermaids]]'', on whose soundtrack it first appeared.\n\nEarly releases of the album in the UK had the same cover as the American release, but later European releases had a different cover, showing Cher laying on a white background wearing a red wig. The European release also included the worldwide hit, \"The Shoop Shoop Song (It's in His Kiss)\" which reached number one in over 10 countries. In the United States, \"The Shoop Shoop Song\" was available only through the original soundtrack, ''[[Mermaids (soundtrack)|Mermaids]]'' for the [[Mermaids (1990 film)|film of the same name]].\n\nWhile the album did extremely well in the UK, its singles were only minor hits. \"[[Love and Understanding]]\" was the only big hit in the charts, but the album also produced many fan-favourites including \"[[Could've Been You]]\" and big Cher favourites, \"Save Up All Your Tears\", \"[[Love Hurts]]\", and \"Fires of Eden\". Also \"Love Hurts and \"Could've Been You\" was released only in Europe, while \"[[When Lovers Become Strangers]]\" was released only in North America.\n\nThe [[David Cassidy]] co-written song, \"I'll Never Stop Loving You\", was released a year later on Cassidy's album, ''[[Didn't You Used to be? (album)|Didn't You Used to be?]]''. One year before, it was already recorded by [[Heart (band)|Heart]] and released on a Japanese special edition bonus CD for their album ''[[Brigade (album)|Brigade]]''.\n\n==Promotion==\n{{See also|Love Hurts Tour}}\nTo promote the album, Cher did several performances worldwide. In North America she promoted the album on ''[[Late Night with David Letterman]]''. She also made a special appearance on the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] program ''[[In Concert (TV series)|In Concert]]'' on June 21, 1991<ref>{{cite news |last=Burlingame |first=Jon |title=Rock-concert show premiers on ABC |publisher=Star-Banner |date=1991-06-07 }}</ref> where she performed \"Love Hurts\", \"Love and Understanding\", \"Save Up All Your Tears\" and \"A World Without Heroes\". This particular performance was highly criticized because Cher lip-synced all songs from the album, veering from the ABC show's premise to showcase \"honest\" live rock.<ref name=\"EW\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Gundersen |first=Edna |title=Cher's lip-synced 'live' performance |publisher=USA Today |date=1991-06-25 }}</ref> Later, during an interview, Cher defended her lip-syncing <ref>{{cite news |last=Williams |first=Jeannie |title=Lip-sync criticism sets Cher off |publisher=USA Today |date=1991-06-28 }}</ref> and ''In Concert'' offered her a chance to reappear (with her band plugged in and playing) later in 1991, but the performance never happened.<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web |last=Kaplan |first=Michael |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,316198,00.html |title=A Little Late-Night Music |publisher=Entertainment Weekly.com |date=1991-11-15 |accessdate=2009-10-29}}</ref>\n\nCher also promoted the album in some European countries. In the UK she performed \"Love and Understanding\", \"Save Up All Your Tears\" and \"Could've Been You\" on ''[[Top of The Pops]]'', on ''[[Wogan]]'' performed \"Love and Understanding\" and \"Save Up All Your Tears\", and on ''[[Michael Aspel#Aspel and Company|Aspel and Company]]'' performed \"Could've Been You\". Cher also performed \"Save Up All Your Tears\" in [[Australia]] during the ''[[Dame Edna's Neighbourhood Watch|Dame Edna Show]]'' and with Dame Edna performed \"[[I Got You Babe]]\".\n\nThe album received further promotion from her third headlining [[Love Hurts Tour]], which started on April 15, 1992, in [[Berlin]], [[Germany]]. The tour was set to start on March 21, 1992, in [[Copenhagen]], but due to illness, the European concerts were rescheduled, except for the UK dates. \nLater dates on the North American leg of the tour were also rescheduled twice.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/05/28/arts/cher-postpones-opening.html |title=Cher Postpones Opening |publisher=The New York Times |date=1992-05-28|accessdate=2009-12-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/05/30/arts/cher-postpones-shows.html |title=Cher Postpones Shows |publisher=The New York Times |date=1992-05-30 |accessdate=2009-12-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/06/09/arts/cher-s-shows-rescheduled.html |title=Cher's Shows Rescheduled |publisher=The New York Times |date=1992-06-09|accessdate=2009-12-01}}</ref> Cher performed \"Love and Understanding\", \"Save Up All Your Tears\", \"Love Hurts\" and \"Fires Of Eden\" on her tour.\n\n==Singles==\n\"[[Love and Understanding]]\" was released as the album's lead single on May 21, 1991. The song received mixed reviews. One critic said that the song, together with others two are tame and over-careful,<ref>{{cite news |last=Macklin |first=William R. |title=Cher passionate, but tunes aren't |publisher=The Milwaukee Sentinel |date=1991-06-19 }}</ref> while another said that \"Love and Understanding\" is a strong track.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wild |first=David |title=Cole's tribute to Dada earns its success |publisher=Greensboro News and Record |date=1991-08-02 }}</ref> The song has reached the top 10 in countries such as the Austria,<ref name=\"aut\">{{cite web|url=http://austriancharts.at/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Cher|title=Cher Singles Discography|date=1965\u20132005|accessdate=2010-01-30|publisher=Austriancharts.at at Hung Medien|work=[[\u00d63 Austria Top 40]]}}</ref> Canada, UK and the top 20 in United States and Germany.<ref name=\"GER\">{{cite web|url=http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/CHER/single|title=Cher Singles Discography|date=1966\u20132002|accessdate=2010-01-30|publisher=Musicline.de|work=[[Media Control Charts]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130115055514/http://www.musicline.de/de/chartverfolgung_summary/artist/CHER/single|archive-date=2013-01-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Save Up All Your Tears]]\" was released as the second single from the album and has reached top 40 on various charts worldwide, including the United States, Canada and the United Kingdom.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|1.5|5}}<ref name=\"allmusic\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r3772|pure_url=yes}}|title=allmusic ((( Love Hurts > Charts & Awards > Billboard Albums )))|work=[[AllMusic]]|publisher=[[Rovi Corporation]]|accessdate=2009-02-04}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n| rev2Score = (favorable)<ref name=\"Love Hurts\">{{cite web|url=http://www.geocities.com/WestHollywood/4983/90S.HTM|title=Love Hurts|accessdate=2009-04-04|work=geocities.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090805145210/http://geocities.com/WestHollywood/4983/90S.HTM|archivedate=2009-08-05}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev3Score = B+<ref name=\"ew\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,314608,00.html|title=Love Hurts Review |last=Farber|first=Jim|date=June 14, 1991|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|accessdate=2009-11-08}}</ref>\n}}\n\nReviews of the record were mixed. On one hand, some critics proclaimed that \"Love Hurts\" was the most mature material Cher had tackled in years. Also, critics said \"Love Hurts\" was a step up from ''[[Heart of Stone (Cher album)|Heart Of Stone]]'', and ''[[Cher (1987 album)|Cher]]''.<ref name=JPC>{{cite web|url=http://www.justplaincher.net/modules.php?name=Reviews&rop=showcontent&id=11|title=Love Hurts : By Eliud|accessdate=2009-04-04|work=justplaincher.net|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101127163908/http://justplaincher.net/modules.php?name=Reviews&rop=showcontent&id=11|archivedate=2010-11-27}}</ref>\n\n''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' for example, said that \"''With a few exceptions, the overall musical direction is more straight-forward rock'n'roll this time, which is the perfect environment for her unique vocal style.''\"<ref name=\"Love Hurts\"/>\n[[allmusic]] also said that \"''The result, however, is particularly formulaic, with Cher's vocals sounding largely uninspired and the production and backing musicians content to be obvious.''\".<ref name=allmusic/>\n\nBut on the hand, some critics slammed the album. One critic went as far as to claim that \"''The only song worth listening to is A World Without Heroes, on an otherwise uninspired album''\".<ref name=JPC/>\n\n==Commercial performance==\nUnlike ''[[Heart of Stone (Cher album)|Heart of Stone]]'' and ''[[Cher (1987 album)|Cher]]'', Love Hurts received less attention in North America yet it was still certified Gold in the US and Platinum in Canada, for reaching the sales of 500,000 and 100,000 copies in those territories, respectively.\nIn European and [[Oceania]]n countries, as well as in Australia and New Zealand, the album was very successful, and peak at number one in four countries: Austria, Ireland, Norway and the United Kingdom. In the UK the album debuted at number one and remained there for six consecutive weeks. After ending its reign at the top, the album remained in the top three for five more weeks becoming the best selling female album of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/archive/official-albums-chart/|title=Love Hurts UK Charts|accessdate=2009-04-05|work=[[Official Charts Company]]}}</ref> It was certified multi-platinum and eventually sold more than 1 million copies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Music-and-Media/90s/1992/MM-1992-07-04.pdf|title=DIANE WARREN WINS UK EMI MUSIC AWARD|publisher=Music & Media, page 4|date=July 4, 1992}}</ref>\n\n==Release history==\n*US Vinyl&nbsp;\u2014 containing the 11-track album.\n*European Vinyl&nbsp;\u2014 containing the 12-track album.\n*US Limited Collectors Box Edition Set&nbsp;\u2014 promotional edition hinged wooden box casing with a flip-up cover. The package contains the album in a CD cardboard slip and thirteen \"[[Tarot|tarot cards]]\" with album designs or Cher photos on one side and lyrics/credits on the other.\n*European Cassette&nbsp;\u2014 unofficial released by Glob Records, with the alternate track list.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Producer(s)\n| title1          = [[Save Up All Your Tears#Cher version|Save Up All Your Tears]]\n| writer1         = {{hlist|[[Diane Warren]]|[[Desmond Child]]}}\n| length1         = 4:00\n| extra1 = {{hlist|[[Bob Rock]]|[[Richie Zito]]}}\n| title2          = [[Love Hurts#Cher version|Love Hurts]]\n| note2           = 1991 version\n| writer2         = {{hlist|[[Boudleaux Bryant]]|[[Felice Bryant]]}}\n| length2         = 4:19\n| extra2 = Zito\n| title3          = [[Love and Understanding]]\n| writer3         = Warren\n| length3         = 4:44\n| extra3 = {{hlist|Warren|[[Guy Roche]]}}\n| title4          = Fires of Eden\n| writer4         = {{hlist|[[Mark Goldenberg]]|[[Kit Hain]]}}\n| length4         = 3:43\n| extra4 = [[Peter Asher]]\n| title5          = I'll Never Stop Loving You\n| writer5         = {{hlist|[[David Cassidy]]|[[John Wetton]]|Sue Shifrin}}\n| length5         = 3:57\n| extra5 = {{hlist|Rock|Zito}}\n| title6          = One Small Step\n| note6           = with [[Richard Page (musician)|Richard Page]]\n| writer6         = {{hlist|Barry Mann|Brad Parker|[[Wendy Waldman (songwriter)|Wendy Waldman]]}}\n| length6         = 3:28\n| extra6 = Asher\n| title7          = [[A World Without Heroes]] \n| writer7         = {{hlist|[[Bob Ezrin]]|[[Gene Simmons]]|[[Lou Reed]]|[[Paul Stanley]]}}\n| length7         = 3:09\n| extra7 = [[Steve Lukather]]\n| title8          = [[Could've Been You]]\n| writer8         = {{hlist|Arnie Roman|Bob Halligan Jr.}}\n| length8         = 3:30\n| extra8 = Asher\n| title9          = When Love Calls Your Name\n| writer9         = {{hlist|Jimmy Scott<ref>http://www.jimmyscottsongwriter.com/discography.htm</ref>|[[Tom Snow|Tomas Snow]]}}\n| length9         = 3:32\n| extra9 = Asher\n| title10         = [[When Lovers Become Strangers]]\n| writer10        = Warren\n| length10        = 4:46\n| extra10 = {{hlist|Warren|Roche}}\n| title11         = Who You Gonna Believe\n| writer11        = {{hlist|Gerald Marquez|Kevin Chalfant|Joe Marquez|Steve Fontano}}\n| length11        = 4:47\n| extra11 = Zito\n| title12         = [[The Shoop Shoop Song (It's in His Kiss)#Cher_version|The Shoop Shoop Song (It's in His Kiss)]]\n| note12          = Oceanian and European bonus track\n| writer12        = [[Rudy Clark]]\n| length12        = 2:51\n| extra12 = Asher\n}}\n\n'''Notes'''\n*\"Love Hurts\" was previously recorded for Cher's twelfth studio album ''[[Stars (Cher album)|Stars]]'' (1975).\n*\"The Shoop Shoop Song (It's in His Kiss)\" is from the ''[[Mermaids (soundtrack)|Mermaids Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]]'' released in 1990.\n\n==Personnel==\n{{Div col}}\n*John Aguto \u2013 assistant engineer (2, 11)\n*Ken Allardyce \u2013 assistant engineer (3, 4, 6, 8-10)\n*[[Peter Asher]] \u2013 [[record producer|producer]] (4, 6, 8, 9, 12), drums, percussion, programming (6), [[backing vocalist|background vocals]] (8), [[percussion]] (9), band [[arranger|arrangements]] (12)\n*Sandy Bathgate - production coordination (1, 5)\n*Martin Brumbach \u2013 assistant engineer (7)\n*[[Robbie Buchanan]] \u2013 [[piano]] (4), [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]] (6, 8, 9, 12)\n*Kim Bullard - keyboards (2, 11)\n*Joanie Bye \u2013 background vocals (1, 5)\n*[[David Campbell (American arranger/composer)|David Campbell]] \u2013 background vocal arrangements (4, 6, 8, 9, 12), orchestral arrangements (4), string arrangements (12), [[conductor (music)|conductor]] (4)\n*Joey Cathcart - background vocals (2, 11)\n*[[Margo Chase]] \u2013 [[art director|design]]\n*[[Luis Conte]] \u2013 percussion (7)\n*[[Honey Ltd.|Laura Creamer]] \u2013 background vocals (3, 10)